@Geffen Avraham just in case you don't see this
Yes, that's the definition.
Spatial resolution in meters per pixel.

You can calculate the required aperture to achieve a certain spatial resolution using the following equation:

1.22 x ((wavelength x height)/aperture)
The wavelength of visible light is from 0.4 microns to 0.7 microns.
The height of geosynchronous orbit is 35,786 kilometers.
At 0.4 microns, you could get 10-meter spatial resolution with a 1.6 meter aperture.
At 0.7 microns, you would need a 2.8 meter aperture.
So if you needed the full visible spectrum, you would need to go even bigger than 2 meters, but if you were OK with only violet light, you could do fine with a 1.6 meter telescope.
(My previous figure of 2 meters was based upon an incorrect height of GSO "off the top of my head" at 40,000 km)
So your telescope can be a bit smaller.
1.6 meters is still big though. Such a telescope would still be very expensive and it would still not fit in even a 24" ESPA ring volume.

messages.content: TL;DR stars had to cool and condense to form, we sort of kind of know how they did but the conventional mechanism of molecular hydrogen cooling fails at low temperatures. If H2 were the sole cooling mechanism, stars would either have formed too late or have been supermassive/black holes. Almost a decade ago my prof accidentally discovered the H3 Rydberg molecule in rare gases, and he and I were able to develop a case for why this and similar Rydberg molecules could clue us in to other cooling mechanisms at low temperatures.
The paper reviews H2 cooling, Rydberg molecules, and proposes investigation and mechanisms of HeH/H3 Rydberg cooling
